review_blob: Bottle from Tesco, reduced to 45p. Pours dark ruby, nice fluffy beige head that lasted.. Didnt get much from the aroma other than dark malts and a vague bit of citrus hop, which turns up in the taste, along with a nice ashy burnt thing. That typical Black Sheep dryness too. Nice mouthfeel, enjoyable lasting finish that was almost like a watered down porter. I thought this was alright tbh, certainly worth the 45p.

Brought back from other halfs holiday apartment somewhere in either SF or Chicago - spare one in the fridge. I dunno, its just another generic corn lager really, innit? Smells of corn, tastes of corn. The positives: Ive had worse commercial lagers, and Ive had ones that tasted like this but were piss juice.

Pint in Liverpool Street Spoons, part of their beer festival. Light gold pour as expected, Kiwi hop aroma but not strong. More balanced than expected, imagined a 5.2% Roosters NZ to be a journey but it was just an enjoyable enough beer, sweet biscuit malt balancing the expected lemon and lime bitterness. Not the best Roosters Ive had, but a solid NZ pale from a solid brewery.

Gitt brought back from Chicago (I guess) by wife, bomber into tulip. Really cloudy pour, toally opaque, but with a big light fluffy head. Lots of mango, pineapple, orange (those are three of the five fruits Ive ever eaten), real fresh juice flavour oddly, and the expected yeast thing. Loads of fruits from the Mosaic but without any accompanying bitterness. This beer is slightly off kilter but in a good way, super enjoyable to drink.

Cask at a Spoons festival, like the rest of us. Poured clear gold with cute lasting white head. Very little Chinook in the aroma leads to very little Chinook in anything else, all a bit washed out and disappointing. Not much point in doing this sort of thing if you arent going to do it properly.

Pint in a Wetherspoons, festival beer but before the festival had started. Very good looking when poured, cute bubbly white head, gold and clear underneath. Started out fine, exactly as expected, an amped up version of an easy drinking pale - biscuit and citrus, and sort of lagery. Seemed pretty promising but then it didnt go anywhere, and was sort of stale by the finish too, like the dregs of a canned British ale. "Deceptively easy drinking" is such a cliche now but its true with this beer, if you want something that slips down quick and sorts you out then maybe this is for you.

750ml bottle from Waitrose. Poured gold, clearish, quite a lot of carbonation to begin with. Lots of marmalade in taste and aroma, sweet malt backbone, fresh at the start but becomes sticky and medicinal towards the end. Really enjoyed this, proper old school British IPA. Id buy again.

Bottle from local off licence, not exactly my first time. Lovely aroma as ever, desert island hop bill, but it all just feels watery and subdued from there. Pineapple, lime, grapefruit, biscuit. Great refresher though, good go-to, just not really what others seem to think it is. If you think this is a great IPA you need to drink more IPA.

Cask at Tap East. Pretty much a textbook cask porter if you ask me, all the elements Id want - chocolate, Kentish hop dark fruit bitterness, licorice, bit of toffee, and then the smoke on top (which I expected more of, but was happy with the amount I had). Almost in recommend to indecisive stranger at the bar territory.

Cask at Tap East - where else? Started off a bit odd, with the initial impression a weird dubbel/stout combination that didnt quite mesh, but gradually it filled out. Sweet like milk chocolate, berries, good creamy mouthfeel, underlying bitterness. Pretty good really.
beer_name: Tap East / Northern Monk Ardennes Stout

review_blob: The best ubiquitous (in London, anyway) British beer by a long shot. Its not going to change your life, but Fullers dont get much wrong and the pasteurised Pride is better than the cask one if you ask me. Sweet malts provide a base for what is a pretty odd hop combination for a mainstream beer, developing and making themselves known without ever really asserting themselves. Quite right too - its all about balance here. Even so, a bit of grapefruit and melon creeps in towards the end, banana maybe.

Gift from father-in-law. Standard, basic trad bitter, nice enough for what its supposed to be though. Pours deep gold, head initially looks promising but doesnt hang around long. Brown bread/caramel/grass/bit of your usual Fuggles/Goldings flavour, all muted though. A little dry and sharp initially. It doesnt try to impress and just gets on with the job it has, which isnt a difficult one.

I go to this a lot, as its generally dirt cheap and delivers plenty for the price. Its inconsistent, but usually it kicks off with a huge hit of eggy sulphur. As with Hobgoblin, you get a bit of citrus and raisin, but with a lot of diacetyl, veg and some kind of soy/umami thing. At one stage it starts to taste a bit like a liquid version of an old hardback book you found in an attic. Also, Stilton and gum balls. I actually really like it, thats the thing.

Four pack for 2.50 in Tesco, reduced to clear presumably. Figured Id try this as it was cheap and Ive never had it before, but with pretty low expectations.

Odd vomit/toe cheese aroma at the start, and then all other aspects are a bit like an extra strength version of those 2% supermarket own brand economy bitters you get. Adjuncts and extracts everywhere, doesnt taste like its touched an actual hop. No real body to it. Bitterness develops, but its a nasty chemical bitterness. 

Cold, though, its drinkable enough. Offered a choice between a cold Stella and another one of these, Id take this.
